<subSubSection id="BC3B1E959A3DA8B005850BB1B39F7D3F" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="1955FB43084E6D7BA785DEC06E6FC237" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A6D8BE041BFC5E132414E2815AA14EE0" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
The specific epithet is given in honour of Dra. Eliane de Lima Jacques, a botanist who has contributed extensively to our knowledge of 
<taxonomicName id="D6D957D5EDD03A7A5A14F8CCDD0BF020" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia" order="Violales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B5B1B598B6F77B7CA702E960A304E2A5" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Begonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Brazil.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3C3428F46B80B27B090231BF0B7C2E5" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="distribution and habitat">
<paragraph id="CA06ED73310825C5CC341D4830660D4D" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FF748B0733FA0B5A14FEA2614C20F246" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<taxonomicName id="692A06CEE7A8EC4E0955894097A3C5EC" authorityName="Gregorio &amp; J. A. S. Costa" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia elianeae" order="Violales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="elianeae">
<emphasis id="E9D64368F756CE9609F652B4CEF70B5A" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Begonia elianeae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found in three localities in southern Bahia, in areas of Atlantic rainforest (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E9AEEB117EAD64E2D5726416D248F1A4" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Geographical distribution of three new species of Begonia. A Latin America showing Brazil and Bahia State B Bahia State showing the three political-economic regions of Bahia with new species of Begonia C Political-economic regions of Bahia showing the occurrence of the three new species." pageId="3" pageNumber="4">2</figureCitation>
), growing on rocks, near pastures or eventually supported by tree trunks, on the edge of trails or disturbed forests. It has not been found in conservation units.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F85E465CE8F2BCC68DD3389C63E1EDD9" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="phenology">
<paragraph id="4E14BD9B7800C30EADD2C8B4D1606071" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0DCF55D677AC2B6F17BEF2AAF34AA6C6" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Flowering in May, August and October, and with fruits in May and October.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CF3F12FA918F1526B556069EAD05F3AA" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="1EDA3A56A323DA766A97122C1D5D0E14" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BF4392C96667290F0B6F5A963012B83B" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<taxonomicName id="ABB56CEB78DE0EE9C0D3F9C3DC39A7BA" authorityName="Gregorio &amp; J. A. S. Costa" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia elianeae" order="Violales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="elianeae">
<emphasis id="174232F1D89F75B900B0104172105D21" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Begonia elianeae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a shrub characterised by the large oblong to obovate leaf-blades, and by the large, yet few-flowered inflorescences and few-fruited infructescences. In 
<taxonomicName id="0037548EB6FB540F3D7962C241B36738" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia" order="Violales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6BFF1F12B5855F77825A6F6DAAA80433" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Begonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, shrubby species are not so common and only two species with this habit occur in the state of Bahia: 
<taxonomicName id="1B01949E191D8472938CF5E9BE178ACF" authorityName="Gregorio &amp; J. A. S. Costa" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia elianeae" order="Violales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="elianeae">
<emphasis id="73D7276F8E63459664A174EFDA850C18" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Begonia elianeae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="361E0DFF405648D80AD10E705A0903B4" authorityName="Schott" authorityYear="1827" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia besleriifolia" order="Violales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="besleriifolia">
<emphasis id="AB52DAB8B346DF09D67832088ABDA7A4" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Begonia besleriifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Both have craspedodromous leaves and can be distinguished from all other species from southern Bahia with this type of venation using the key below. The most likely section of 
<taxonomicName id="407578325B0C37D141FD79EC83B613CC" authorityName="Gregorio &amp; J. A. S. Costa" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia elianeae" order="Violales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="elianeae">
<emphasis id="342D7DD910CB8C428D1C732DEBF76B7D" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Begonia elianeae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the sect. 
<taxonomicName id="BDE7B24DD5CEB71CEAC7FD9B7BBF0564" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Violales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Ruizopavonia">
<emphasis id="59871FA7EA1DD74FF1610E0B1871E535" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Ruizopavonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
A. DC., which consists of suffrutescent plants, with woody stem, straight, craspedodromous leaves, and bracts and styles caducous in fruit.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
